<TITLE> Lula names Senate ally as energy minister </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Sao Paulo, Jan 17 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Brazilian President Luiz Inacio Lula da Silva appointed ally Sen. Edison Lobao as energy minister on Wednesday, the official government newswire said. Lobao belongs to the centrist Brazilian Popular Movement Party, the largest in Lula's 11-party governing coalition. His nomination faced opposition by left-wing members of Lula's ruling Workers' Party. Lobao's son, who is likely to serve in his stead as senator once he assumes the role of minister, is being investigated for tax fraud in the northeastern home state, Maranhao. Silas Rondeau resigned as energy minister in May 2007 over corruption allegations. Nelson Hubner, the former No. 2 man at the ministry, has been serving as the interim minister since
